## FILE TRUNCATION PREVENTION

This project previously had a file truncation issue caused by sync conflicts between the Cowork bash sandbox and the host filesystem. Files over ~500 lines could get silently chopped during writes. The root cause (308 lines of duplicated inline CSS in every blog post) has been fixed by extracting to css/blog.css. All blog posts are now under 400 lines.

**No file may be left in a truncated state. Ever. No exceptions.**

If a file write or edit results in a truncated file (missing closing tags, mid-sentence breaks, reduced line count from pre-edit baseline), the session is in a failed state until the file is recovered and the edit re-applied cleanly.

Rules for every session:

1. NEVER use the Edit tool on any file over 400 lines. Use sed via bash instead.
2. After EVERY file modification, verify the file ends correctly by running `tail -5 filename` in bash.
3. Before declaring any task complete, run the verification script below.
4. If a file IS truncated, recover from git: `git show HEAD:filename > recovered.html`, apply changes to the recovered copy, then overwrite the original.
5. For HANDOFF.md itself: before writing, capture the existing content to a .tmp file, append new content, verify the .tmp file, then overwrite the original. Never write HANDOFF.md in a single pass if it exceeds 300 lines.
6. When appending content to any file, use `cat >> file << 'HEREDOC'` blocks capped at 80 lines per block. Multiple sequential appends are safer than one massive write.
7. After every write operation, compare actual line count against expected line count. If they diverge, stop and diagnose before proceeding.

Verification script (update the session path for your session):

```
cd "/sessions/SESSION-SLUG/mnt/Island Mountain"
for f in *.html blog/*.html; do
  [ "$f" = "googlecff518dc414acaa3.html" ] && continue
  lines=$(wc -l < "$f")
  has_close=$(grep -c '</html>' "$f")
  if [ "$has_close" -eq 0 ]; then
    echo "TRUNCATED: $f ($lines lines, no closing tag)"
  fi
done
echo "Verification complete."
```

Files still at risk (over 400 lines): contact.html (966), faq.html (938), investors.html (676), government.html (641), insurance.html (640), energy-utilities.html (640), education.html (640), financial-services.html (639), law-firms.html (633), tribal-nations.html (626), products.html (619), pricing.html (610), defense-contractors.html (606), medical-practices.html (600), research-labs.html (594), technology.html (536), why-island-mountain.html (495), solutions.html (490), blog.html (482), index.html (530), blog/openwebui-admin-setup-guide.html (433), blog/cloud-ai-vs-local-hardware-tco.html (404), blog/h100-vs-h200-inference-comparison.html (400). Use sed via bash for all files over 400 lines.

